  "messages": [
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Return Run with Walking Breaks\",\"target_distance_km\":3,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":372,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":372,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":390,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk for the first 5 minutes at a comfortable pace. Let the foot warm up gradually before any running begins.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run easy within the Daniels-Gilbert easy zone, 5:25 to 6:12 per km. If any foot pain arises, drop to a walk immediately. No pushing through discomfort.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":390,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Return to a walk for the final 5 minutes. Keep moving gently rather than stopping abruptly.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Walk for 5 minutes before running. The plantar fascia needs a gradual transition from rest to load. Do not skip this.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for at least 5 minutes after finishing. Gentle calf stretches after the walk are fine if they feel comfortable, not forced.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Your physiotherapist has cleared you for 20 minutes of easy running only. This session stays within that boundary. The cap here is 20 minutes total, with the actual running portion at 10 minutes. Your Daniels-Gilbert easy pace range is 5:25 to 6:12 per km. Stay at the slower end of that range or slower. The goal right now is load tolerance, not fitness. Any foot pain means drop to a walk. Note your pain level before, during, and after. That information will guide what comes next.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Midweek Run with Walking Breaks\",\"target_distance_km\":3,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":372,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":372,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":390,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"5-minute walk warmup. Same as Tuesday. Let the tissue warm before running.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy running within the Daniels-Gilbert easy zone. Drop to a walk at any sign of foot pain. Keep effort conversational.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":390,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"5-minute walk cooldown. Do not stop cold after running.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"5-minute walk before running. Same protocol as Tuesday. Consistency in how you approach each session matters for tissue adaptation.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"5-minute walk after running. Notice how the foot feels compared to Tuesday. Any lingering soreness is worth flagging to your physio.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is your second session of the week. The main question is how the foot responded to Tuesday. If Tuesday produced soreness that lasted more than a couple of hours, reduce the running portion to 5 minutes and pad the remainder with walking. If Tuesday felt fine, hold the same 10-minute run structure. Volume stays flat for now. The plantar fascia adapts slowly, and the rate-limiting factor is tissue tolerance, not cardiovascular fitness. Your aerobic base from the 44:00 10K is still partially accessible. Patience here protects that base.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Saturday Easy Long Effort with Walking Breaks\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":372,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":372,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":390,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"5-minute walk warmup. Same protocol as the weekday runs.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy running within the Daniels-Gilbert easy zone. This is your designated long run day, but until clearance expands, the 20-minute cap applies. Stay slow, stay relaxed.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":390,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"5-minute walk cooldown. Take note of any foot fatigue that builds over the week. Three sessions in a row on tired tissue is a real signal.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Walk 5 minutes before running. By the third session of the week, the foot may carry some cumulative load. The warmup walk matters more here, not less.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 5 minutes after running. This is your last session of the week. A longer walk cooldown is fine if you feel like it. Let the foot decompress.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Saturday is your long run day. Right now, long run and weekday run look the same because the 20-minute ceiling applies across all sessions. That will change as your clearance expands. The purpose of keeping Saturday is structural. You are rebuilding the habit and the tissue tolerance at the same time. Weekly total across three sessions is roughly 9 to 10 km. That is a modest step up from recent weeks, which have ranged from 2.4 to 8.5 km. Watch cumulative fatigue. If the foot is more sore on Saturday than on Tuesday, that is a signal to drop one of the weekday sessions or shorten them. Bring that information to your physio at your next appointment.\",\"perceived_effort\":3}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
  "modelId": "\"claude-sonnet-4-6\"",
  "finishReason": "stop",
